text: hi everyone colton daytano here the
internet's busiest music nerd
and it's time for a review of the new
trippy red album
pegasus this is the newest full-length
lp from ohio native
trippy red his third commercial release
and his biggest
statement to date with 26 tracks
and 74 minutes of run time i was highly
skeptical of the length
going into this because of how much of a
rough ride trippy's
last record was so i was hoping for
something
a lot more planned out and maybe focused
this time around and i guess i sort of
did get the focus because
generally the tracks on this thing are
pretty sentimental
sensual even bordering on romantic or
at least attempting that i mean love
isn't exactly a new topic for trippy red
given his emo trap credentials but
pegasus definitely stands out as the
most euphoric
and feel good project in his catalog
i think just in terms of what it's
clearly going for
so the direction of this thing the
concept is
there for sure but it still remains
that trippy's execution leaves a lot to
be desired
continuing to squander the raw talent
showcased on his
debut as well as his early viral
mixtapes overall pegasus is somehow less
vocally impressive than nearly
everything trippy has done so far and on
top of that there is
absolutely nothing about it that
justifies
this run time for one it's not that
versatile
the production here ranges from bland
wavy trap beats to beats that barely
sound like they've even been properly
mixed the claps on personal favorite
with rich the kid are ridiculously high
on never change with future we have
futures auto-tuned vocals
definitely loud strings this just hard
hitting trap be on top of this blobby
bass and all of it is roaring as loud as
possible there's no balance whatsoever
then for some reason the second future
feature on this project
sounds like he's uh delivering his verse
through a drive-through speaker
then with hellrain everyone's vocals are
so distant and washed out
and slathered with reverb there's really
no presence to
anyone's performance here especially lil
wayne who sounds like he's trying to
stay out of the way as much as possible
for some reason
trippy red and chris brown on their
respective track mix like sour patch
kids on pizza
the lyrics are terrible and the gap in
vocal talent between both of them is
plain as day
lil mosey is a snooze fest then busta
rhymes while i don't dislike his
performance
he just seems like a really strange fit
on a record like this his style
his bravado his lyrical technicality
doesn't exactly lend itself to a project
like this
young thug is probably the best feature
and most fitting
on the entire record but it's not like
this is one of his best appearances
ever in fact it sounds like he's trying
to downplay his
as much as possible as not to outshine
trippy red too much
so the beats and the guests are just not
enough to keep this project on life
support so i think it goes without
saying that
trippy himself isn't really doing the
job either i mean at least a third of
the time
on this record he barely sounds like
himself there was a track on the front
end that sounded like he was doing a
travis scott ripoff

best playboy cardi impression
oomp's revenge part 2 is pretty much
like god's father era will be
and there's at least a handful of tracks
on this thing where he's just doing a
future ripoff
really biting future's vocal inflections
the song take one sounds like a
reference
track meant for future and not that
trippy red has ever been considered a
god-tier lyricist or
anything but going on for 70 plus
minutes just exposes how thin
trippy reds lyrical ideas run there are
so many throwaway refrains
and hooks on this thing from just you
and me baby
one two to the track we whose chorus is
literally we plus there are all sorts of
bars on this thing that stand out for
all the wrong
reasons like on spaceships where trippy
red mentions flying into from
overseas
they both from portugal they both
portuguese
yeah that is kind of how that works
plus repeatedly on this thing trippy
similes are just
bottom of the barrel take the song take
one again for example
where he says he's like free like a
mason
which in isolation is not the worst bar
on the planet but
i'm telling you that is about as good as
trippy's simile game gets on this
project
again not that versatile dynamic or even
super flashy lyricism is required
to make a hip-hop track or an emo trap
track good
but if you're gonna go 74 minutes your
ambitions as an artist
should be showing and in the case of
trippy red and pegasus it's just not
the most unlikely thing about pegasus
though is that many of the songs here
actually segue into each other
pretty nicely or at least smoothly it's
weird there'd be so much effort and
focus on
making that the case despite there being
so many
mixing flaws and half-baked songwriting
but
okay yeah i'm really just struggling to
find
anything to compliment on this record
outside of maybe
a handful of choruses that kind of got
my head nodding or
a couple of decent beats here and there
this thing is just
bloated as hell and crumbling under the
weight
of its own size it's like building a
skyscraper out of styrofoam
